      "## Common Misconceptions About FTWZ Operations",
      "Many importers hesitate to adopt FTWZ operations due to misconceptions that have persisted since the early days of India's free trade zone policy. One of the most common myths is that FTWZ is only suitable for large-volume importers handling thousands of containers annually. In reality, even small and medium importers handling 10-20 containers per year can benefit significantly from duty deferment and cash flow improvements. The FTWZ model is scalable — warehousing charges are typically structured on a per-pallet or per-square-foot basis, making it accessible to businesses of all sizes.",
      "Another misconception is that the documentation and compliance burden of FTWZ is prohibitively complex. While FTWZ operations do require specific customs documentation (warehousing bonds, Bills of Entry for warehousing, and Shipping Bills for re-export), experienced FTWZ operators like Astromar handle the entire documentation process on behalf of clients. The importer's involvement is typically limited to providing commercial invoices and packing lists — documents they already prepare for standard imports.",
      "Some importers also worry about the security of their goods in FTWZ facilities. Modern FTWZs are among the most secure warehousing environments in India, featuring 24/7 CCTV surveillance covering every square metre of the facility, biometric access controls for all personnel, customs-sealed perimeters with single-point entry and exit, comprehensive insurance coverage for stored goods, and regular customs inspections ensuring accountability at every level.",
      "## Tax and Regulatory Framework: What Importers Need to Know",
      "The regulatory framework governing FTWZs in India is established under the Special Economic Zones Act, 2005, and the SEZ Rules, 2006. The Development Commissioner (DC) of the relevant SEZ zone oversees FTWZ operations, and customs authorities maintain a permanent presence within the zone to supervise goods movement and documentation. Key regulatory requirements include obtaining a Letter of Approval (LOA) from the Development Commissioner for storing goods in the zone, executing a warehousing bond with customs covering the duty value of stored goods, maintaining detailed inventory records accessible to customs for audit purposes, and complying with the Foreign Trade Policy provisions applicable to FTWZ operations.",
